[1] Colombia (Norte de Santander)
Date: Fri 28 May 2010
Source: Diario La Opinion [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.laopinion.com.co/noticias/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=352032&Itemid=28>


The Ocana Mayor's office, the Norte de Santander Governor's office,
and the Departmental [state/province] Institute of Health gave a press
conference in order to let everyone know about the [campaign] for
dengue control, due to the significant increase of [dengue] cases
registered in this region of the country. The situation led the
municipal administration to decree an "orange alert" to be attentive
to the prevention of this disease, combating the vector mosquito from
all fields.

The Governor of Ocana, Yebrail Haddad Linero, announced that so far
this year [2010] there are 29 cases in the municipality, of which 47
percent have been in children less than 15 years of age, the reason
for which he called on parents and adults in general to establish
contingency plans and measures towards preventing and stopping this
situation.

Haddad Linero thanked both the departmental Institute of Health and
the Emiro Quintero Canizares Hospital for the timely response for the
fight against _Aedes aegypti_. "We have the obligation to provide the
necessary conditions for all the Ocana inhabitants to develop their
personal integrity and for 'You can be Healthy'," added the leading
authority of Ocana. Both the mayor as well as the officials of the
departmental Institute of Health stated that constant fumigation will
not work if in the homes [occupants] do not carry out the
recommendations to avoid breeding of the mosquito that causes
[transmits] dengue [virus infection].

Although Ocana does not have decentralized health [systems], it is
necessary to adopt a series of measures to combat the mosquito vector,
_Aedes aegypti_, indicated Haddad Linero.

He requested that the representatives of IPS [health care
institutions] and EPS [health insurance agencies] organize all their
personnel to go out on the street, discover the breeding sites, and
stop the foci of contamination [reproduction]. "It is necessary to
involve everyone -- children, youths, adults, elderly, rural people,
housewives, and others to take up the campaigns to fight the
mosquito," he added. It is recommended that [water] tanks, sinks,
pots, and water buckets that can accumulate water be constantly
cleaned and scrubbed. The accumulated water must be emptied in order
to eradicate the mosquito breeding sites. He made an important call to
[school] principals, teachers, and students, to deliver the guidelines
for the care and ongoing inspection of bathrooms and sanitary
equipment. "The input of all members of society is necessary to spread
the precautions and counter the sources where the larvae reproduce."

--
