[4] Taiwan
Date: Tue 25 May 2010
Source: Taiwan Headlines, Central News Agency (CNA) report [edited]
<http://www.taiwanheadlines.gov.tw/ct.asp?xItem=190743&CtNode=39>


The Department of Health (DOH) has asked the public to take
precautions against dengue fever as the disease's 2nd wind seems to be
gaining strength. Lin Ting, deputy director general of the DOH's
Centers for Disease Control, said that this year's [2010] dengue fever
outbreak has come in 2 waves. Some 38 cases were recorded in the 1st
round, which started last year [2009] and extended into this spring
[2010].

After the outbreak eased off for more than one month, a 2nd wave has
struck, and the number of dengue fever cases has risen to 7, mainly in
Kaohsiung City. "The public should be on alert against the latest
round of dengue fever," Lin cautioned, noting that the mosquito-borne
disease [virus] is usually prevalent at this time of year. Because no
vaccine exists for the disease, Lin said the most effective step that
can be taken against it is to eliminate potential breeding grounds for
the mosquitoes by cleaning up containers with standing water.

