[5] Thailand (Pattani)
Date: Tue 25 May 2010
Source: The ASTV Manager Online [in Thai, trans. Mod.SCM, edited]
<http://www.manager.co.th/Local/ViewNews.aspx?NewsID=9530000071857>


Today [25 May 2010], Dr Yorn Jiranakorn, chief of Pattani provincial
health office, alerts people that dengue may be fatal and prepares the
SRRT (surveillance rapid response team) to investigate and control a
dengue outbreak in the province after more than 400 hospitalized cases
have been reported since 1 Jan 2010. The districts with the most
reported cases are Muang, Mayo and Nong Jik district.

The trend of dengue outbreaks in Pattani province has been
continuously rising. Recently, Pattani is the 2nd province in Thailand
in terms of the number of dengue fever patients. Therefore, Pattani
Public Health Office asks people to destroy any possible habitats for
the mosquitoes around their residences every 7 days in order to stop
the mosquitoes from breeding.

--
Communicated by:
PRO/MBDS
<promed-mbds@promedmail.org>

[According to the newswire above, dengue infection is ongoing in
Pattani province. In the beginning of May 2010, increase in dengue
cases in Phuket province was also reported (see prior PRO/MBDS posting
Dengue - Thailand: Phuket 20100507.1480). Both provinces are located
in the south region of Thailand.

According to the dengue surveillance data from the Bureau of
Epidemiology (BOE), Ministry of Public Health, Thailand website dated
25 May 2010, the total number of reported cases of dengue infection in
Thailand since 1 Jan 2010 is 16 110 cases and 20 deaths: 7032 dengue
fever (DF) cases and one fatality; 8795 cases of dengue hemorrhagic
fever (DHF) and 5 fatalities; and 283 cases of dengue shock syndrome
(DSS) and 14 fatalities.

A total of 397 cases and 1 death were attributed to dengue infection
in Pattani province between 1 Jan 2010 and 17 May 2010. There were 118
cases of DF, 272 cases of DHF, and 7 cases with one death of DSS.

Regarding dengue fever (DF), the nationwide attack rate was 11.07 per
100 000 population. The highest attack rate (per 100 000 population)
was reported in the south region (20.75), followed by the central
region (13.32), the northeastern region (7.60), and the north region
(6.06). The 5 provinces with the highest attack rates of dengue fever
(per 100 000 population) were Yala (51.01), Satun (44.69), Trat
(38.63), Chantaburi (31.69), and Rayong (29.73). About 50 percent of
DF cases were in the 10-24 year old age group; 25.9 percent were 10-14
years old; and 25.1 percent were 15-24 years old (see, in Thai,
<http://203.157.15.4/surdata/disease.php?ds=66>).

Regarding dengue hemorrhagic fever (DHF), Pattani was the province
with the highest attack rate in Thailand (42.00 per 100 000
population), whereas the nationwide attack rate was 13.84 per 100 000
population. Other provinces with high attack rate (per 100 000
population) were Songkha (40.92), Pattalung (38.99), Samut-Prakran
(36.59), and Samut-Sakhon (34.46). By region, the highest attack rate
(per 100 000 population) was reported in the south region (22.45),
followed by the central region (20.96), the northeastern region
(7.16), and the north region (6.65). The majority of cases were in the
10-24 year old age group; 23.14 percent were 10-14 years old; and
29.41 percent were 15-24 years old (see, in Thai,
<http://203.157.15.4/surdata/disease.php?ds=26>).

Regarding dengue shock syndrome (DSS), the nationwide attack rate was
0.45 per 100 000 population. The highest attack rate (per 100 000
population) was reported in the south region (0.85), followed by the
northeastern region (0.52), the north region (0.34), and the central
region (0.26). The 5 provinces with the highest attack rates of DSS
(per 100 000 population) were Surat-thani (2.41), Tak (2.12), Surin
(1.89), Burirum (1.42), and Krabi (1.41). About 50 percent of DSS
cases were in the 10-24 year old age group; 31.1 percent were 10-14
years old; and 20.14 percent were 15-24 years old (see, in Thai,
<http://203.157.15.4/surdata/disease.php?ds=27>).

Please note that while the URL links go to web pages in the Thai
language, if one goes to the central column of the page, there are
links to the data files by years, with 2552 representing 2009 and 2553
representing 2010. Clicking on the year will then provide a link to
download the respective files for dengue fever reports by province and
region, dengue hemorrhagic fever reports by province and region, and
dengue shock syndrome reports by province and region.

For a map showing Thailand's provinces, see
<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Provinces_of_Thailand>.
For the interactive HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Thailand with links
to other recent ProMED-mail and PRO/MBDS postings, see
<http://healthmap.org/r/01kT>. - Mod.SCM]
